<subSubSection id="7A6F425160A59F938D344C228DC56F19" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="7F5F9D32F19F6622B43A021F85FCFF7A" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7EDEFAC982868D43EA805EB01C9BD396" pageId="0" pageNumber="81">
Growing in open rich marshy meadows, along stream margins and in sandy terrain amongst low scrub, sea level to 
<quantity id="A064A64C7250B8030416B1B1BD3F6260" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" unit="m" value="1300.0">1300 m</quantity>
. of elevation. Flowering in July and August. Germination epigeal. It is worth noting that both diploid and triploid plants have been found in 
<collectingCountry id="DA6456742BF3A8C4F1FF3127DC6E7EAA" name="South Korea">Korea</collectingCountry>
and that plants have been observed to produce subterranean stolons that extended to as much as 
<quantity id="5F2660B36B9E52C28618AAC92964CDE8" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" unit="m" value="2.0">2 m</quantity>
in length (
<bibRefCitation id="DB1B9F06433732685CF3958CAC255537" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/1442-1984.12090" author="Kim, J-H" journalOrPublisher="Plant Species Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="81" pagination="98 - 106" refId="B12" refString="Kim, J-H, Truong, NX, Song, Y-S, Kim, N-S, 2016. Natural triploid Lilium leichtlinii var. maximowiczii populations in Korea. Plant Species Biology 31 (2): 98 - 106, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/1442-1984.12090" title="Natural triploid Lilium leichtlinii var. maximowiczii populations in Korea." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/1442-1984.12090" volume="31" year="2016">Kim et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
: 104).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
